[h1][section:clr-malus]WARNING[/section][/h1]
Sorcerer casting is much less formal than that of other traditions, which reflects in their lack of a spell list. They may, however, create personalized spells ("[section:clr-sorc]Sorceries[/section]") of their own based on the [url:#Templates]templates[/url] provided below, which in turn are based on the [url:/generia/rules/magic/freecasting#Guidelines]Freecasting Guidelines[/url]. [section:clr-sorc]Sorceries[/section] have the same SP cost per tier as any other spell.

[h1]Q&A[/h1]
[h4]Why create Sorceries instead of Freecasting?[/h4]
To skip the risk of the initial freecasting check and streamline combat.
[h4]When is it a good idea to create Sorceries?[/h4]
Whenever the sorcerer needs access to a  somewhat reliable, easily repeatable spell (e.g., in combat or other intense situations). It is advisable to start off with at least one or two Sorceries at character creation, and keep a reserve of SP in case a spontaneous need for a formalized spell arises.

[h1|Templates]Templates[/h1]
Sorcery templates are deliberately kept generic and open-ended. Their effects are subject to Player and GM discretion.
[br]When buying a template spell, you may modify it to fit your Sorcerer's playstyle and flavor in cooperation with the GM. For example, a Sorcerer with an offensive Concept might gain additional features for [section:clr-pa]PA[/section] and [section:clr-sa]SA[/section] spells like increased damage or range, while a Sorcerer with a supportive Concept might gain access to more impactful buffs or healing.
[br]These modifications must always come with some sort of tradeoff, even if it is just an increased mana cost.
[br]You may buy a specific template more than once.
[br]The GM may mandate adjustments, should a customized spell prove too weak or too powerful.
